Returns the absolute value of the given number.
\n
```
abs('-1');     // 1
abs(-2);       // 2
abs(null);     // 0
abs('');       // 0
abs([]);       // 0
abs([2]);      // [2]
abs([1,2]);    // [1,2]
abs({});       // NaN
abs('string'); // NaN
abs();         // NaN
```

Maps a number from the d1 domain to the d2 domain.
\n
This can be thought of as a percentage.
The percentage of num in d1's range is calculated,
then used to find the equivalent value for num in d2.
\n
```
remap(10, [0, 100], [100,200]) // 10 is 10% of 0-100. Hence, 10% of 100-200 is 110.
remap(40, [20, 80], [0, 30])   // 40 is 33.3% of 20-80. Hence, 33.3% of 0-30 is 10.
```
The number/integer to be remapped.
A list of two numbers, representing the first domain.

comment.text: The input number is measured as a percentage of the min/max scale, then a color is returned depending on where the percentage lies on the color gradient. Using a Brewer scale would be similar to using `visualize.Gradient`, which comes preloaded with those scales. See that function's drop-down menu for a list of valid Brewer scales. Accepted custom color inputs include: - Hex, as a string. (w3schools hex builder) - RGB255, as a list. (w3schools RGB builder) - Colors from X11 with no numbers, as a string. (w3schools X11 list) See here for an example model.
